{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539098"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:37:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:37:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16431"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16431","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16431"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.11,0.65,0.12,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9122"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65243"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9122","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9122"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16431"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50680"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1533"},{"type":"tags","id":"2137"},{"type":"tags","id":"2380"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2996"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"9590"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21674"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65243","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65243"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with three days of confusion and lethargy. He was diagnosed with small cell lung cancer two months ago and is receiving chemotherapy. His medical history includes chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. His medications include carboplatin and etoposide.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears euvolaemic. His pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 128/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 89% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There are no peripheral oedema or postural blood pressure changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium: 118 mmol/L (135-145)\u003Cbr /\u003EPotassium: 4.0 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003Cbr /\u003ECreatinine: 95 \u00b5mol/L (60-110)\u003Cbr /\u003EGlucose: 5.2 mmol/L (3.5-7.8)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following combinations of results would be most likely in this case?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Serum osmolality 280 mOsm/kg, urine osmolality 100 mOsm/kg, urine sodium 10 mmol/L","Serum osmolality 245 mOsm/kg, urine osmolality 100 mOsm/kg, urine sodium 60 mmol/L","Serum osmolality 245 mOsm/kg, urine osmolality 400 mOsm/kg, urine sodium 60 mmol/L","Serum osmolality 245 mOsm/kg, urine osmolality 400 mOsm/kg, urine sodium 10 mmol/L","Serum osmolality 280 mOsm/kg, urine osmolality 400 mOsm/kg, urine sodium 60 mmol/L"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with hyponatraemia in the context of small cell lung cancer, which is the most common malignant cause of syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion (SIADH). The diagnosis requires specific biochemical findings in a euvolaemic patient, with exclusions of thyroid dysfunction and adrenal insufficiency. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum osmolality 245 mOsm/kg, urine osmolality 400 mOsm/kg, urine sodium 60 mmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct combination. SIADH is characterised by low serum osmolality (due to hyponatraemia), inappropriately concentrated urine, and elevated urine sodium in a euvolaemic patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum osmolality 280 mOsm/kg, urine osmolality 100 mOsm/kg, urine sodium 10 mmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E shows normal serum osmolality with appropriately dilute urine and low urine sodium, which is not consistent with SIADH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum osmolality 245 mOsm/kg, urine osmolality 100 mOsm/kg, urine sodium 60 mmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E shows a low urine osmolality which is not consistent with SIADH. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum osmolality 245 mOsm/kg, urine osmolality 400 mOsm/kg, urine sodium 10 mmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E shows concentrated urine but low urine sodium, which is more consistent with volume depletion than SIADH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum osmolality 280 mOsm/kg, urine osmolality 400 mOsm/kg, urine sodium 60 mmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E shows normal serum osmolality which is inconsistent with SIADH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther causes of hyponatraemia that need to be excluded include medications (particularly thiazide diuretics), adrenal insufficiency, hypothyroidism, and renal, cardiac or liver disease. The presence of euvolaemia helps distinguish SIADH from hypovolaemic and hypervolaemic causes of hyponatraemia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["SIADH is characterized by hyponatraemia with high urine osmolality and inappropriately high urine sodium.","Small cell lung cancer is the most common malignant cause of SIADH.","The diagnosis of SIADH requires euvolaemia and exclusion of other causes of hyponatraemia."],"references":["Yasir M, Mechanic OJ. Syndrome of Inappropriate Antidiuretic Hormone Secretion (SIADH). In: StatPearls [online]. 2023. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK507777/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50680"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16431"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50680","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50680"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-25T23:13:36+10:30","upda